'''Techreturns Nederland BV''' is a Dutch company founded with the aim to reduce [[electronic waste]] (e-waste). It does this by buying used electronics, especially mobile phones, from consumers and companies to repair them and give them a second life. Some choose to donate mobile phone through organisations such as Masterpeace and [[Natura Artis Magistra|Artis]] Zoo.<ref>{{cite web|title=Doneer je oude telefoon aan de olifanten|url=http://www.artis.nl/kaartjes-steunen/olifanten/doneer-je-oude-telefoon-aan-de-olifanten/|work=Artis Zoo|publisher=Artis Zoo|accessdate=17 January 2014}}</ref>   The company's revenues comes from selling the second hand devices mainly in [[Asia]] and [[Africa]] where there is a market for affordable, quality electronics.<ref name="Mobile phones Africa">{{cite news|last=Persson|first=Michael|title=Afrika biedt tweede leven aan de mobieltjes die wij afdanken|url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/vk/nl/2844/Archief/archief/article/detail/3375320/2013/01/11/Afrika-biedt-tweede-leven-aan-de-mobieltjes-die-wij-afdanken.dhtml|accessdate=3 December 2013|newspaper=De Volkskrant|date=11.01.2013}}</ref> Sales also take place in [[Europe]], especially in the Netherlands through its sister company BeatsNew.

Techreturns is connected to [http://closingtheloop.eu/ Closing the Loop] a foundation collecting e-waste in developing countries for recycling.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Drabbe|first=Jean Paul|title=Afvaltelefoons importeren uit Afrika|journal=P+ 'People Planet Profit'|date=Nov–Dec 2013|volume=12|issue=2|pages=38–39}}</ref> Involved in this project are also the organisations [[Fairphone]] and Text to Change.<ref name="Radio 1">{{cite news|title=Oude mobieltjes verkopen in Afrika|url=http://m.radio1.nl/mobiel-radio1/gemist/fragment/119605|accessdate=15 January 2014|newspaper=Radio 1 Nederland|date=14 October 2013}}</ref><ref name="Fairphone and Closing the Loop">{{cite web|last=de Kluijver|first=Joost|title=Circular Economies with "Closing the Loop"|url=http://www.fairphone.com/2013/01/29/circular-economies-closing-the-loop/|work=Fairphone|publisher=Fairphone|accessdate=29 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=de Vroeg|first=Josette|title=Reducing e-waste via SMS in Uganda|url=http://www.texttochange.org/news/reducing-e-waste-sms-uganda|work=Text to Change|publisher=Text to Change|accessdate=15 January 2014}}</ref>

Recently, Techreturns has appeared multiple times in the Dutch media, for instance in a discussion about sustainability initiatives by the Dutch government, an annual summary of Dutch sustainable businesses 2013 by MVO Netherlands and in the consumer television programme [[Kassa (television program)|Kassa]] on 14-01-14 in a segment about reuse versus recycling in the electronic industry.<ref name="rt(z) article">{{cite news|title='Overheid doet te weinig aan duurzaam aanbesteden'|url=http://www.rtlnieuws.nl/economie/toekomstmakers/overheid-doet-te-weinig-aan-duurzaam-aanbesteden|accessdate=15 January 2014|newspaper=rt (Z)|date=12 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Successen 2013: drie circulaire toppers|url=http://www.mvonederland.nl/content/nieuwsbericht/terugblik-2013-drie-circulaire-toppers|work=MVO Nederland|publisher=MVO Nederland|accessdate=17 January 2014}}</ref><ref name="Kassa Groen">{{cite web|title='Oude mobieltjes onnodig snel gerecycled'|url=http://kassa.vara.nl/tv/afspeelpagina/fragment/oude-mobieltjes-onnodig-snel-gerecycled/speel/1/|work=Kassa Groen|publisher=Vara|accessdate=15 January 2014}}</ref>

Techreturns was founded in 2009, is based in [[Amsterdam]], [[Netherlands]] and is a part of Social Enterprise Nederland.<ref>{{cite web|last=Zwaan|first=Meike|title=Techreturns|url=http://social-enterprise.nl/social-enterprises/techreturns/|work=Social Enterprise NL|publisher=Social Enterprise NL|accessdate=17 January 2014}}</ref>  Additionally Techreturns has a department in [[Genova]], [[Italy]].

